{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_fogler_ver01/data/sn83030214/00206532610/1921032401/0661.xml":{"full_text":"Connolly Terms\nCraig's Charges\nCowardly, False\nSays Allegations in Regard to\nGty Contracte Show Comp?\ntroller's Hatred for Tho.se\nWho Disagree With Him\nBorough 'President Maurice E. Con\noily of Queens, in replying yesterday\nto the charges made by Comptroller\nCharles L. Craig in affidavits-filed in\n:h?*? Supreme Court in regard to certain\n??it? contracts in that borough, chais\nacterized them as \"cowardly and ma?\nliciously false,\" and declared that the\nComptroller showed the \"hatred he\nbears for those who disagree with\nhim.\" The Comptroller declined to\n.??omn-ent on Mr. Connolly's reply.\n\"Ssnce wh?t a person says in papers\ntiled in an action in court cannot be\nprosecuted as slander or libel,\" said\nvfr. Connolly, \"the Comptroller hides\nbehind this protection.\"\nAfter explaining in detail the con?\ntracts for paving material to which\nthe Comptroller took exception, Mr.\nConnolly offered various reasons for\nthe Comptroller'? hostility toward him.\namong them being the fact, he said,\nthat \"some of his friends in Queens\nhad suggested his?Connolly's?name\nfor the Comptrollership at the coming\nt.tv election.\n\"On one occasion O'Neil, the Comp?\ntroller's confidential agent and cam?\npaign manager.\" said the Borough\nPresident, \"met me upon the street\nand chided me at 'having the nerve'\nto look for the position of Comptroller.\ni war- amused at his annoyance and as?\nsured him that I was not an aspirant.\nHe, however, appeared not to be satis?\nfied and suggested ?that I promise that I\nwould not be a candidate for the posi?\ntion unless I received th*e approval of\nthe regular organization and that I\nwould not run independently if Mr.\nCraig were the regular d?sign?e.\n\"Or. another occasion O'Neil stated\nthat the Comptroller's hostility toward\nne w.-.s due to the fact that the Comp?\ntroller believed that his punishment\nfor cuntempt of court by Judge Mayer\nwas due. for some reason or other, to\n3uy action. He said that I had in?\nformed Judge Mayer of the statement?\nCraig had made against him. This, oi\n-jourse, is not the fact.\n\"At the same time the Comptrollei\nhas done everything to obtain an in?\ndictment and has supplied all the in?\nformation that he and his minion\ncould secure; nevertheless there ha.?\nbeen no ndictment, for the very good\nand sufficient reason that no crime oi\nwrong has been committed.\n\"As a result of the action of th<\nComptroller jn depriving the contrae\ntors of the moneys due them they hav<\nbeen compelled to stop important worl\nand will suffer large financial lossei\nby reason thereof; They have indicat\ned their intention of suing the cit?\nan d will no doubt recover large dam\nages. What the city will lose as th?\nresult of the Comptroller's action doe,\nnot seem to concern him. However\nwhen the contractors sue and recove:\ndamages from th? City of New Yorl\nby reason of his illegal action a tax\npayer's suit will be brought agains\nhim to recover from him personally al\nsums the city will be required to los\nby his illegal conduct.\n\"His high-handed method of persona\nattack and his warfare of hatred wil\nnot be permitted to occasion the cit;\n:inancial loss.\"\n\nTo Aid Disabled Soldiers\nHarding Urged to Set Apart i\nWeek in Their Honor\nFrom The Tribune'* Washington Bureau\nWASHINGTON,\" March 23.?-Presi\ndent Harding to-day was urged to se\napart a \"Disabled Soldiers' Week,\" t<\nfie observed throughout the Unite.\nStates.\nGeorge H. Gillen, of New York, na\ntior.al commander of the Disabled Sol\ndiers' League, accompanied by Jame:\nW. Mellen, chairman of the legislativ?\ncommittee, and by other officers o\nthe league and a number of wounde.\nveterans, called on the President t?\ntake the matter up with him.\nIt was pointed out that Govenio:\nMiller of New York already has issue?\na proclamation setting apart the weel\nof May 29 to June 4 as \"Disabled Sol\n-hers' Week\" in New York State. Th?\npurpose is to have all possible atten\ntion directed in that week to legisla\ntive and other activities in behalf o\nthe disabled veterans.\nThe President was asked to do in i\nnational way what Governor Miller ha;\ndone in New York. He took the re\nquest under advisement.\nAfter the conference the Presiden\nconsented to pose for a photo with th.\nwounded soldiers.\n\n-Oenby Reaches Guantanamo;\nBoards Ship in Maneuver)\nON BOARD THE UNITED STATE*\nBATTLESHIP PENNSYLVANIA, OP1\nGUANTANAMO, Cuba, March 23. (B;\nThe Associated Press).?Edwin Denby\nthe American Secretary of the Navy\narrived off Guantanamo Bav to-dav 03\nPiebald Bull, Groomed by Gobs,\nTosses Idol of Mexico for a Goal\nAffrighted by Own Carmine Tail After Being Treated\nby Artists From U. S. Ship, He Heaves Proud Cas?\ntillan Matador Into &3 Reserved Arena Seat\nSe?or Juan Martine? y Cas-tillio was\nonce a matador. He dispatched bulls\nneatly and conclusively and was the\nidol of Mexico. He was rated a maestro\nuntil one day in Mexico City three\nAmerican gobs introduced him to a\ncamouflaged bull. Since then Se?or\nJuan Martinez y Castillio has not been\nthe same. His appearance has changed,\nand from last reports He was barely\nable to sit up in his cot in a 'large,\nquiet h-fspital m Mexico City and par?\ntake of a little warm milk.\nSuch is the tale as it was told yes?\nterday by Hilda Moreno, who arrived\nfrom Mexico on the Spanish Royal Mail\nsteamship Antonio Lopez. She is eight?\neen year, old and is from Madrid,\nSpain.\nOn Program to Kill Fire\nIt was while the Se?orita was in\nMexico City that she had occasion on\nSunday, February 27, to attend, in\ncompany with the three gobs, a spec?\ntacle in the arena in which Signor\nJuan Martinez y Castillio was sched\nuled to kill five bulls.\nThe first animal was led into the\nring and was duly and properly slain\nj by Signor Juan Martinez y Castillio.\nThe second was driven into the ring\nand the matador promptly speared him\nbetween the shoulder blades.\nEvery one gave Martinez applause\nexcept the Se?orita and the three gobs.\nTo them it was a one-sided affair in\nwhich the bull had no luck at all.\nBy the time Se?or Juan Martinez y\nCastillio had done with the fourth\nbull, the quartet could be plainly\nboard the torpedo boat destroyer\nCrowninshield D. Later Mr. Denby\ntransferred his flag to the battleship\nPennsylvania during the maneuvers at\nsea.\nheajrd by the management voicing in?\ndignation.\n''Entonces,'* said the management,\n\"what would you have?\"\n\"Lemme talk to the next bull,\"\npleaded one of the sailors.\nAnd so it waa arranged. The three\ngo'>s went to the bull's boudoir, under\nthe arena, and, left alone, they pre?\npared him for the fray.\nThe Se?or Receives a Shock\nSe?or Juan Martinez y Castillio, im?\npatient to call it a day, nearly fell on\nhis face when the fifth and last bull\nromped gayly into the arena.\nThe spectators stood up and roared.\nThere was the bull. His face was\npainted yellow, his four quarters were\npaijpted white, his barr?l was painted\nblue and his tail was of a quiet car?\nmine color. Pausing for a moment to\nlook around to see if he were all there,\nhe caught sight of his tail and failed\nto recognize.;himself. This infuriated\nhim and h?s**?%,vi'shed at the appendage\nwith enthusiasm intent on ramming it\nwith his horns. The result was that\nhe chased himself all over the twena.\nSe?or Juan Martinez y Castillio\nmeant nothing to this young bull. He\nnever even noticed the matador, whose\nembarrassment was somewhat in?\ncreased by a pair of horns painted on\nthe bull's after deck. He only met the\nmatador once and that was informally,\nwhen he took a wild swipe at his tail\nand missed. That is to say, he missed\nhi- tail, but caught Sernor Juan Mar?\ntinez y Castillio and lifted him out of\nthe arena and into the $3 seats, where\nit is nice and shady.\nTake it or leave it, that's the\nsenorita's story and she sticks to it.\nShe is going back to Spain to dance\nin Madrid.\nWith Admiral Wilson, the Secretary\nwitnessed target practice from the\nbridge of the flaeship.\nOn returning to tiuantanamo Mr.\nDenby will inspect the naval station.\ndemons\nestablished' i8?8\n39TH ?r BROADWAY\nOur highest price $*7/\\\nSuit for Spring is\nIt is really more than a than needs to pay\n(which seems like a tactless ?thing for a Clothier\nto say) but, ?then, you know how some men are!\n,-_._. i\nLeg Luxury\ntor Srarymmsn\nZ. Garters fit perfectly, but with no\nannoying tension? because the wide, soft\nwebbing naturally \"gives\" to every move?\nment of the leg, yet clings to it snugly.\nAi all dealers.\nAlway-? look for the name E. Z.\nstamped on the garter you huy. The\nonly genuine H. Z. Is made solely by\nThe Thoo. F. Taylor Co.,\nBridgeport. Conn.\nE7 GARTER\nmm a Wide for Comfort\nYOU CAN ALWAYS\nSAVE MONEY SWEARING\nWLDO?GIAS SHOES\nSOLD DIRECT FROM FACTORY\nTOMLXJATONEPROFTI\nW. L. DOUGLAS\n$8.00 SHOES\nSpecial Shoe?\nMaintained\n?6.00\nRetail Price\nReduced\nSp-eci-al Shoes i f 1 f If 1 ?i op?\nHand Workmanship IVtUV J| 'Styli.h and Durable\nFOR MEN AND WOMEN\nTHE STAMPED PRICE IS W. t.\nDOUGLAS PERSONAL GUARANTEE\nTHAT THE SHOES ARE ALWAYS\nWORTH THE PRICE PAID FOR THEM\nThey aire the best ?known shoes in the world.\n?Sold in 107 W.JL Douglas stores, direct from\n\\the factory to you at only one profit, which\nguarantees to you the best shoes that ?can be\nproduced at the lowest possible cost. W.L.\nDouglas name ?and the retail price are stamped\non the bottom of all shoes before they leave\nthe factory, which is your protection against\nunreasonable profits.\nW. L. Douglas shoe? are absolutely the best\nshoe value? for the money in this country.\nThey are made of the ?best ?and finest leathers\nthat money can buy. They combine quality,\nstyle, workmanship and wearing qualities\nequal to other makea^ selling at higher\npri?es. They are the leaders in the fashion\ncenters of America. The prices are the ?same everywhere; they cost\nno more in San Francisco than they do in New York.\nW. L. Douglas shoes are made by the highest paid, skilled^ shoe?\nmakers, under the ?direction ?and supervision of experienced men, ?all\nworking with an honest determination to make ?the best shoes for the\nprice that money can buy. ?f/?T? 0\n/HAI BTTI BU Insist opon saving W. I? OovglM ibo??. WOi?mn^At/Sime\nWAW I lUiVThtaaai.-udpriMTipUlnlritampedoDth? Preside** J\nBOYS'I\nSHOES\n?0M500\n*3*?? 8tN*\n?if not ftw aala k| y?<jur y?tAnty, exiaritittn from hOtty. GaUlogv? fr?a> 210 Spart St. ?racktoi\nW.L. DOUGLAS STORES IN GREATER NEW YORK\n?847 Eighth Avenue.\n?50 Wee* 135tb Street.\nBROOKLYN\n*J08 Bi*eodway, ^ewTfc-we-tooSt.\nit 1867 Btroad way, cor. Gat? Are.\n478 Fift* Aw? ??or. I ltk St.\n-A- 859 Maaaottaa Ave. CBm????^\n?MS Faitea Sfcreet.\nJEItSBYCITY?18 Newark Avenue.\n*HOBOKEN-120 Waah!n?ton Street.\n?UNION HHJ?-276 Bergealine Ave.\n*NEWARK-831 Broad Street.\n*PATERSON-l 92 Market 8t^w. ?dark\n*TKENTON-30 Eaet State -Slmt'\n??wreinniMh^ ?kh? -mri-y ea?wwle?e Uwe??* W. I? ne**u?la? SImm for Waom\nNow is the Time to Build and\nRelieve Housing Shortage\n\nS W STRAUS CQ offer Capital\nTHE time has come to resume building operations. The\nimmediate construction of moderate priced apartments\nin large numbers in New York City is a public necessity.\nThousands of apartments are urgently needed to relieve\nthe present conditions officially described as a menace to\npublic health, public morals and public security.\nThe turn in the tide of the building industry has arrived.\nThe time has come to build and build on an extensive scale.\nBuilders who have been waiting for the most favorable mo?\nment now find that the moment is here.These are the reasons:\n1J The cost of,building material has receded 15 to 20% from the high\npeak of 1920.\n?2 J The unprecedented demand for housing accommodations grows\ngreater as the city's population increases, with only trifling increases\nin the housing accommodations.\n3 J The present supply of building materials is strictly .limited. As new\nconstruction increases and the demand for materials grows, prices\nnaturally are bound to increase as the available supply is lowered.\n?4} The coming return of prosperity and business activity will cause a\nstill greater demand for buildings?a demand which must be .sup?\nplied if prosperity is to come.\nj_5 J Income from rented property will stay at present levels, due not\nonly to the demand but to generally higher standards of living to\nX which the public has been educated.\n?t\nTherefore, S. W. STRAUS Co. urge: Build Now!\nS. W. STRAUS CO. offer capital to aid in building at 6% interest.\nAs a matter of public duty and in the interests of public welfare,\nwe announce an important change in policy:\nIn order to further the construction of moderate priced apart\nments for tenants of moderate means at moderate rentals, we have\nlowered the minimum of building loans we will accept, from $500,\nj? 000 to $200,000. We will specialize in aiding the financing of new\nbuildings designed to furnish homes for the people-apartments at\nrentals as reasonable as present conditions will permit. Rents will\ngo up more unless more buildings go up.\nTHE resumption of building activity will go far towards a restora?\ntion of general prosperity. Active building operations will give\ndirect employment to many thousands of men. Railroad freight traffic\nwill enormously increase and railroad revenues revive. Such industries\nas steel, brick, cement, lumber, tile, electricity, plumbing and score of\nallied trades will again find themselves* active, prosperous and giving\nemployment to thousands. The building industry is the key to the situa?\ntion. Prosperity cannot return to the country, at large until new con?\nstruction goes forward.\nWe believe it is the duty of every lending institution to concentrate\non housing relief; that it is the duty of every builder to erect moderate\npriced apartments; that it is the duty of every investor to purchase securi?\nties to aid in the financing of new housing construction.? We believe\nfurther that lending institutions, builders and investors will find public\nduty and good business to be identical.\nOnly by united efforts can the housing shortage be relieved, this menace\nto our civilization be removed, and national prosperity be restored.\nRflwtatft4 fifftR wfltwe-_l In\nThe New V?tk Thui, M_-eh 22, l?21\nOur Message to\nBuilders\nWe invite loan applications for the fi?\nnancing of moderate priced apartments\nin the city of New York. Wc are ready\nto underwrite long-term building loans\nin amounts of $2oo<-,ooo upwards in the\nform of first mortgage 6% serial bond\nissues to aid in financing the construction\nof new apartment houses designed to\nlease at moderate rentals. Wc are in the\nmarket for a large supply of such mort?\ngages combining building and permanent\nloans in one financing.\nIt is our opinion that the price of build?\ning materials will increase and that now\nis the economical and profitable time\nto build. We invite interviews with those\nwho have sound and meritorious apart?\nment house construction projects con?\nforming to. our requirements and safe?\nguards. We are ready to give you prompt\naction.\nOur M?ssage to\nInvestors\nThis Institution performs a double func?\ntion in aiding in the upbuilding and re-\nbuilding of the cities of the United States\nand providing safe investments for the\nfunds of the public. We accept and offer\nto investors only such bonds as survive\nthe rigid tests of the Straus Plan?\nbonds based on the one fundamental\nbasic commodity, improved real estate\nbonds which give the investor safety,\nfreedom from worry and anxiety, and a\nsatisfactory income yield.\nThat our Plan is sound and our method\nconservative are clearly indicated by the\nrecord of this House?39 Years Without\nLoss to any Investor. We suggest that\nyou invest your money?first, so that it\nwill be safe; and second, so that it will\naid in providing additional housing ac?\ncommodations to relieve the pressing\npublic need.\nS W STRAUS <Sc CO.\nINCORPORAT2D ESTABLISHED l88?\n150 BROADWAY, NEW YORK Telephone Cortlandt 8064\n?ETROrr. BOSTON WASHIN<3TON ??LWAUtCEB PHt-A-KTOlA MMBAKH.B\n39 YEARS WITHOUT LOSS TO ANY INVESTOR","height":"25356","width":"20139"}}
